{"schema":"https:\/\/ihsn.org\/schemas\/timeseries\/1.0.0","schema_version":"1.0.0","type":"timeseries","idno":"b6732d81-08fc-4411-8663-4e9260b02d5a","changed":"1757427354","changed_utc":"2025-04-04T12:35:52-04:00","created":"1756907330","created_utc":"2024-06-21T11:35:36-04:00","created_by":"31","changed_by":"31","metadata_information":{"idno":"META_WB_PIP_SEVERITY","producers":[{"name":"Development Economics Data Group","abbr":"DECDG","affiliation":"World Bank"}],"prod_date":"2024-06-21","version_statement":{"version_notes":"Updated title formatting for consistency.","version_date":"2025-09-30","version":"1.1"},"title":"Metadata for Poverty Severity (0 - 1)"},"series_description":{"idno":"WB_PIP_POVERTY_SEVERITY","version_statement":{"version":"1","version_date":"2024-10-04"},"name":"Poverty severity (0 - 1)","authoring_entity":[{"name":"World Bank","uri":"https:\/\/pip.worldbank.org\/"}],"measurement_unit":"Percent","database_id":"WB_PIP","release_calendar":"In a typical year, there are two major updates (March\/April and September\/October), which bring in new survey data. These updates are documented in What\u2019s New documents (published in the Global Poverty Monitoring Technical Notes series)","alternate_identifiers":[{"identifier":"PIP database indicator ID","database":"WB.PIP"},{"identifier":"PIP dataset variable name ","name":"poverty_sev"}],"definition_long":"The square of Poverty gap. Poverty gap at a day (2017 or 2021 PPP) is the mean shortfall in income or consumption from the poverty line a day (counting the nonpoor as having zero shortfall), expressed as a percentage of the poverty line. This measure reflects the depth of poverty as well as its incidence. As a result of revisions in PPP exchange rates, poverty rates for individual countries cannot be compared with poverty rates reported in earlier editions.\n\nPlease refer to: https:\/\/datanalytics.worldbank.org\/PIP-Methodology\/.","periodicity":"Annual","methodology":"Please refer to: https:\/\/datanalytics.worldbank.org\/PIP-Methodology\/","methodology_references":[{"source":"Poverty and Inequality Platform Methodology Handbook","uri":"https:\/\/datanalytics.worldbank.org\/PIP-Methodology\/"}],"aggregation_method_references":[{"source":"Poverty and Inequality Platform Methodology Handbook","uri":"https:\/\/datanalytics.worldbank.org\/PIP-Methodology\/non-technical-summary.html#step-2-constructing-welfare-aggregates"}],"limitation":"PIP extrapolations and interpolations require additional assumptions, namely that (a) growth in household income or consumption can be approximated by growth in national accounts and (b) all parts of the distribution grow at the same rate. Given these assumptions, users are cautioned against using reference-year estimates for comparing a country\u2019s poverty trend over time. For that purpose, users should rely on the survey-year estimates and are advised to take into account breaks in survey comparability. Because extrapolating and interpolating require full welfare distributions, for a country to feature in PIP, it is not sufficient that it has an international poverty rate at a survey year, it must have unit record data or grouped data. For more details on the methodology and types of input data accepted by PIP, please visit the PIP Methodology Handbook and the Global Poverty Monitoring Technical Notes.","quality":"In a typical year, there are two major updates (March\/April and September\/October), which bring in new survey data. These updates are documented in What\u2019s New documents (published in the Global Poverty Monitoring Technical Notes series). When necessary, intermediate updates are made to correct errors as soon as possible. Updates are documented here: https:\/\/worldbank.github.io\/PIP_data_updates\/.","time_periods":[{"start":"1963","end":"2023"}],"contacts":[{"name":"Raul Andres Castaneda Aguilar","position":"TTL","affiliation":"DECID","email":"acastanedaa@worldbank.org"},{"name":"Nishant Yonzan","position"